  "summary": "Following his conversation with Mr. Scott, Hercule Poirot encounters Maud Williams at the Blue Cat Cafe. Maud, a blonde woman who works in the same office as James Bentley, expresses her hope that new evidence will exonerate him. She offers a character testimony that contrasts with the general public's perception of Bentley as an unpleasant or unreliable man, instead describing him as a polite, well-read, and shy individual who is a devoted caretaker to his weak mother.\n\nWhen Poirot questions Maud about potential motives or enemies, she denies knowledge of any family feuds. However, she reveals that Bentley once mentioned his landlady, Mrs. McKinty, kept her money hidden under the floorboards. Maud clarifies that Bentley had expressed concern regarding the landlady's carelessness rather than any desire to steal the money. Poirot reflects on this information, noting how criminals often reveal themselves through careless speech.\n\nTo encourage Maud to assist the investigation, Poirot lies to her, claiming he has made significant progress. He provides her with his contact information at the Long Grass Hotel. As Poirot travels back to Brodini, he reflects on his previous, depressing prison visit with Bentley, who believed he had no friends or enemies. Poirot concludes that Maud Williams is a true friend to Bentley, observing that even an unattractive man can find a woman who admires him.",
